ctually, `set_knave_to_knight` is a tactic that converts a goal from `x ∈ Knave` to `x ∈ Knight` and adds a hypothesis `x ∈ Knave ↔ x ∈ Knight`. Let me check the definition.\n\nWait, I think `set_knave_to_knight` is converting a goal from `x ∈ Knave` to `x ∈ Knight` and adds a hypothesis `x ∈ Knave ↔ x ∈ Knight`. So in this case, it converts `B ∈ Knave` to `B ∈ Knight` and adds `h : B ∈ Knave ↔ B ∈ Knight`.\n\nThen `intro BKnight` is introduced. So `BKnight : B ∈ Knight` is a hypothesis.\n\nThen `have CKnave := stCn.mpr BKnight`. `stCn` is `C ∈ Knave ↔ B ∈ Knight`. So `stCn.mpr` is the forward direction: `B ∈ Knight → C ∈ Knave`. So applying `BKnight : B ∈ Knight`, we get `CKnave : C ∈ Knave`.\n\nThen `have stA := stB.mp BKnight`. `stB` is `B ∈ Knight ↔ (A ∈ Knight ↔ Knight.card = 1)`. So `stB.mp` is the forward direction: `B ∈ Knight → (A ∈ Knight ↔ Knight.card = 1)`. Applying `BKnight : B ∈ Knight`, we get `stA : A ∈ Knight ↔ Knight.card = 1`.\n\nThen `have AKnave : A ∈ Knave`. This is introduced.\n\nThen `set_knave_to_knight`. This converts the goal from `A ∈ Knave` to `A ∈ Knight` and adds a hypothesis `h : A ∈ Knave ↔ A ∈ Knight`.\n\nThen `intro AKnight`. So `AKnight : A ∈ Knight` is a hypothesis.\n\nThen `have KnightCard := stA.mp AKnight`. `stA` is `A ∈ Knight ↔ Knight.card = 1`. So `stA.mp` is the forward direction: `A ∈ Knight → Knight.card = 1`. Applying `AKnight : A ∈ Knight`, we get `KnightCard : Knight.card = 1`.\n\nThen `rw [Finset.card_eq_one] at KnightCard`. `Finset.card_eq_one` is `Finset.card s = 1 ↔ ∃ a, s = {a}`. So this rewrites `Knight.card = 1` to `∃ a, Knight = {a}`. So `KnightCard` becomes `∃ a, Knight = {a}`.\n\nThen `have ⟨a,ha⟩ := KnightCard`. This destructures the existential quantifier. So `ha : Knight = {a}`.\n\nThen `rw [ha] at AKnight`. `AKnight` is `A ∈ Knight`. `ha` is `Knight = {a}`. So this rewrites `A ∈ Knight` to `A ∈ {a}`. So `AKnight` becomes `A ∈ {a}`.\n\nThen `rw [ha] at BKnight`. `BKnight` is `B ∈ Knight`. `ha` is `Knight = {a}`. So this rewrites `B ∈ Knight` to `B ∈ {a}`. So `BKnight` becomes `B ∈ {a}`.\n\nThen `rw [Finset.mem_singleton] at AKnight`. `Finset.mem_singleton` is `x ∈ {a} ↔ x = a`. So this changes `AKnight : A ∈ {a}` to `AKnight : A = a`.\n\nSimilarly, `rw [Finset.mem_singleton] at BKnight`. This changes `BKnight : B ∈ {a}` to `BKnight : B = a`.\n\nThen `rw [←AKnight] at BKnight`. `AKnight` is `A = a`. `←AKnight` is `a = A`. `BKnight` is `B = a`. So applying `a = A` to `B = a`, we get `B = A`. So `BKnight` becomes `B = A`.\n\nFinally, `contradiction`. This tries to find a contradiction in the hypotheses. The relevant hypotheses are:\n\n- `B = A` (from `BKnight`)\n- `A = a` (from `AKnight`)\n- `B = a` (from `ha` and `B = a`)\n\nWait, `B = A` and `A = a` implies `B = a`. But we also have `B = a` from `ha` and `B = a`. So this is consistent, not a contradiction.\n\nWait, this suggests that the proof is incorrect. There's no contradiction here. The proof gets stuck.\n\nWait, let me retrace.\n\nWe have:\n\n- `B = A` (from `BKnight`)\n- `A = a` (from `AKnight`)\n- `ha : Knight = {a}`\n\nFrom `B = A` and `A = a`, we get `B = a`.\n\nFrom `ha : Knight = {a}` and `B = a`, we have `B ∈ Knight`.\n\nBut we also have `B ∈ Knave` from the initial hypothesis `BKnave`.\n\nSo we have `B ∈ Knave` and `B ∈ Knight`. This is a contradiction. So the proof should work.\n\nLet me check the steps again.\n\n`rw [←AKnight] at BKnight`. `AKnight : A = a`. So `←AKnight` is `a = A`. `BKnight : B = a`. So applying `a = A` to `B = a` gives `B = A`. Correct.\n\nThen `contradiction`. The hypotheses are:\n\n- `B ∈ Knave` (from `BKnave`)\n- `B ∈ Knight` (derived from `B = a` and `ha : Knight = {a}`)\n\nThis is a contradiction. So the proof should work.\n\nTherefore, the `sorry` should be replaced by the correct proof steps. The issue is that the final `contradiction` tactic might not be powerful enough to see the contradiction between `B ∈ Knave` and `B ∈ Knight`.\n\nLet me think about how to make the contradiction explicit.\n\nWe have `B ∈ Knave` (from `BKnave`). We also derived `B ∈ Knight`. So we can use these two facts to create a contradiction.\n\n```tactics\nimport SmullyanKnightsAndKnaves.knightsknaves\nimport SmullyanKnightsAndKnaves.knightsknaves_3\n-- problem 27\n\n-- newformalization\nopen settheory_approach\nvariable [DecidableEq Inhabitant]\n/-\nSuppose the stranger, instead of asking A what he is,\nasked A, \"How many knights are among you?\" Again A\nanswers indistinctly. So the stranger asks B, \"What did A\nsay?B replies, \"A said that there is one knight among us.\"\nThen C says, \"Don't believe B; he is lying!\"\nNow what are B and C?\n-/\n\nexample\n(stB : (B ∈ Knight) ↔ (A ∈ Knight ↔Knight.card = 1))\n(stC : ( C ∈ Knight ↔ B ∈ Knave) )\n\n  : B ∈ Knave ∧ C ∈ Knight := by \n  have : ¬B ∈ Knight\n  intro BKnight\n  rw [not_iff_not.symm] at stC\n  set_knave_to_knight at stC\n  have CKnave := stC.mpr BKnight\n\n  have oneK := stB.mp BKnight\n  set_knight_or_knave A with AKnight AKnave\n  have oneK := oneK.mp AKnight\n  unfold oneKnight at oneK\n  simp [AKnight, CKnave, BKnight] at oneK\n  set_knave_to_knight  at oneK \n  simp [ CKnave, BKnight] at oneK\n  contradiction\n\n  set_knave_to_knight at AKnave\n  rw [not_iff_not.symm] at oneK\n  have notone := oneK.mp AKnave \n  unfold oneKnight at notone\n  simp [AKnave, CKnave, BKnight] at notone\n  set_knave_to_knight  at notone\n  simp [AKnave] at notone\n  contradiction\n\n  set_knight_to_knave  at this\n  have CKnight :=  stC.mpr this\n  constructor ; assumption ; assumption\n\nexample\n{inst2 : Fintype Inhabitant}\n(stB : (B ∈ Knight) ↔ (A ∈ Knight ↔Knight.card = 1))\n(stC : ( C ∈ Knight ↔ B ∈ Knave) )\n(stCn : ( C ∈ Knave ↔ B ∈ Knight) )\n\n  : B ∈ Knave ∧ C ∈ Knight := by \n  have BKnave : B ∈ Knave\n  set_knave_to_knight\n  intro BKnight\n  have CKnave := stCn.mpr BKnight\n  have stA := stB.mp BKnight\n  have AKnave : A ∈ Knave\n  set_knave_to_knight\n  intro AKnight\n  have KnightCard := stA.mp A